# Despite algorithmic advances, hardware utilization has not significantly improved

Real‐world training jobs typically achieve 20-60% utilization, leaving 40-80% of their hardware’s available FLOPS on the table. This figure has remained stagnant in recent years despite substantial algorithmic advances, as these improvements are counteracted by rapid growth in model and dataset sizes. Larger workloads require distributed training across more GPUs, increasing communication overhead and reducing effective hardware utilization.

While newer kernels (e.g. FlashAttention) can wring out an extra 10-20% of hardware utilization by increasing efficiency at the individual-GPU level, improvements in model‑level utilization remain stifled by the cost of memory traffic between GPUs. Gains that don’t reduce such communication pressure rarely translate into speedups over the whole process. This suggests two paths forward for developers who wish to improve efficiency:

- **Pick model size carefully.** Once a model exceeds single-node memory limits and thus requires distribution across additional GPUs, the overhead from inter-GPU communication reduces efficiency. A slightly smaller model that fits within existing hardware constraints can be more cost-effective.  
- **Optimize MoE routing.** Overloading a few experts slows the entire training step, even if others are idle. Well-balanced mixture-of-experts routing evenly distributes computational load, increasing efficiency by reducing idle compute and preventing resource bottlenecks.

## Methodology
Data are taken from Epoch’s AI Models dataset. We use calculated or reported numbers for model FLOPs utilization (MFU), hardware FLOPs utilization (HFU), and recorded release or publication dates of the models.
## Data
Model FLOPs utilization (MFU) and hardware FLOPs utilization (HFU) are recorded when reported by the authors, or otherwise calculated if enough information is available regarding the model and its training process.
MFU is calculated by comparing compute applied to model training against the maximum possible compute performed by the training hardware during the training period.
HFU is calculated by comparing the measured throughput during training to the theoretical maximum throughput of the training hardware.
HFU is easier to measure directly during the development process, but MFU is a better measure of efficiency at model training. Of 3000 models in Epoch’s database, we have utilization data on 80 models, with MFU typically ranging from 20-60% and HFU typically ranging from 40-70%. It is rare for both metrics to be reported, but MFU is observed to be around 75-80% of HFU in these few cases.
